<paragraph blockId="18.[136,1452,230,1373]" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,495,1022,1048]" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Distribution and habitat:</emphasis>
—This species occurs in Central and South America, in 
<collectingCountry box="[1149,1234,1022,1048]" name="Bolivia" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1249,1320,1022,1048]" name="Brazil" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1334,1447,1022,1048]" name="Colombia" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[136,264,1058,1084]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[278,368,1058,1084]" name="Guyana" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[382,474,1059,1085]" name="Panama" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Panama</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[487,541,1059,1085]" name="Peru" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[555,662,1058,1084]" name="Suriname" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Suriname</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[722,961,1058,1084]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Trinidad and Tobago</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Soderstrom, T. S. &amp; Zuloaga, F. O." box="[978,1311,1058,1084]" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref26650" refString="Soderstrom, T. S. &amp; Zuloaga, F. O. (1989) A Revision of the genus Olyra and the New Segregate Genus Parodiolyra (Poaceae: Bambusoideae: Olyreae). Smithsonian Contribution to Botany 69: 1 - 83." type="journal article" year="1989">Soderstrom &amp; Zuloaga 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Vorontsova, M. S. &amp; Clark, L. G. &amp; Dransfield, J. &amp; Govaerts, R. &amp; Baker, W. J." pageId="18" pageNumber="117" refId="ref27897" refString="Vorontsova, M. S., Clark, L. G., Dransfield, J., Govaerts, R. &amp; Baker, W. J. (2016) World Checklist of Bamboos and Rattans. International Network for Bamboo and Rattan, Beijing, China, 446 pp." type="book" year="2016">
Vorontsova 
<emphasis box="[136,196,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[323,394,1094,1120]" name="Brazil" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is registered in the Amazon Forest, between 150 to 1.100 meters, in the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[1390,1447,1094,1120]" country="Brazil" name="Acre" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Acre</collectingRegion>
, Amazonas, Pará, 
<collectingRegion box="[332,441,1130,1156]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[496,641,1130,1157]" country="Brazil" name="Mato Grosso" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Mato Grosso</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Oliveira, I. L. C. &amp; Oliveira, R. P. &amp; Carvalho, M. L. S." box="[656,895,1130,1157]" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" pagination="2020" refId="ref25932" refString="Oliveira, I. L. C., Oliveira, R. P. &amp; Carvalho, M. L. S. (2020 b) Olyra In: Flora do Brasil 2020, Jardim Botanico do Rio de Janeiro, Rio de Janeiro, Rio de Janeiro state, Brazil. Available from: http: // floradobrasil. jbrj. gov. br / reflora / floradobrasil / FB 13360 (accessed 9 October 2021)." type="book chapter" year="2020">
Oliveira 
<emphasis box="[757,813,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">et al.</emphasis>
2020b
</bibRefCitation>
). In the Serra do Cachimbo, it was found in Open ombrophilous forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="117" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[136,1452,230,1373]" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,328,1202,1228]" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Comments:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Trinius" authorityYear="1836" box="[356,520,1202,1228]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Olyra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caudata">
<emphasis box="[356,520,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">Olyra caudata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus (1759: 1261)" authorityName="Linnaeus (1759:" authorityPageNumber="1261" authorityYear="1261" box="[578,970,1202,1229]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Olyra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="latifolia">
<emphasis box="[578,703,1202,1229]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">O. latifolia</emphasis>
Linnaeus (1759: 1261)
</taxonomicName>
share culms ca. 
<quantity box="[1163,1208,1202,1229]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" unit="m" value="2.0">2 m</quantity>
tall, ovate-lanceolate leaves, asymmetrical, shortly pilose on both surfaces, female spikelets awned and anthecium ovoid and smooth. However, this species has umbelliform synflorescences, the female spikelets are larger (23–32 × 
<quantity box="[1253,1350,1274,1301]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" unit="mm" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5 mm</quantity>
) and the glumes are subequal, with awns 
<quantity box="[494,614,1310,1337]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" unit="mm" value="13.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="13.0">13–14 mm</quantity>
long, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus (1759:" authorityYear="1261" box="[751,873,1310,1337]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Olyra" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="latifolia">
<emphasis box="[751,873,1310,1337]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="117">O. latifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has pyramidal synflorescences, the female spikelets are smaller (10–12 × 
<quantity box="[376,512,1346,1373]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" unit="mm" value="1.8" valueMax="2.2" valueMin="1.4">1.4–2.2 mm</quantity>
) and the glumes are unequal, with awns 
<quantity box="[968,1103,1346,1373]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" metricValueMax="4.8" metricValueMin="3.8" pageId="18" pageNumber="117" unit="mm" value="4.3" valueMax="4.8" valueMin="3.8">3.8–4.8 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
